{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17514017","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17514017"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:17:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:17:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12264"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12264","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12264"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0.7,0.03,0.02,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4786"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"60927"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4786","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4786"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12264"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"46372"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"43"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"98"},{"type":"tags","id":"147"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7657"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7695"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11001"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17697"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42725"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43313"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"60927","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/60927"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 61-year-old man presents to his General Practice clinic with a two-month history of worsening shortness of breath. His symptoms are most noticeable when he exercises. He has a medical history of asthma, migraines and hypertension. His asthma has been well-controlled with salbutamol inhaler as needed since his 20s and he has barely had any exacerbation episodes for the past ten years. On further questioning, he admits to taking some of his wife\u0027s blood pressure (and migraine prophylaxis) medication for the past three months. He does not take any other regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs of pulse rate 60/min, blood pressure 150/90 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.3\u00b0C. Cardiovascular and respiratory examinations are normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following medications is most likely to explain his current symptoms?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Perindopril","Propranolol","Hydrochlorothiazide","Irbesartan","Nifedipine"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has likely been taking his wife\u0027s \u003Cstrong\u003Epropranolol\u003C/strong\u003E, which is commonly prescribed for both migraine prophylaxis and hypertension. Beta-blockers, particularly non-selective beta-blockers like propranolol, are absolutely contraindicated in patients with asthma. They directly antagonise the effects of beta-agonist medications like salbutamol, potentially precipitating bronchospasm and reducing the effectiveness of rescue inhalers.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EACE inhibitors like \u003Cstrong\u003Eperindopril\u003C/strong\u003E can be prescribed to patients with asthma, though they may cause cough. Some evidence suggests mortality benefits in patients who can tolerate them.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDiuretics like \u003Cstrong\u003Ehydrochlorothiazide\u003C/strong\u003E can be used in asthmatics but require monitoring. They may cause hypokalaemia, particularly when used with beta-agonists which drive potassium into cells. Low doses (12.5-25mg daily) are preferred in non-oedematous hypertensive patients with asthma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAngiotensin II receptor blockers like \u003Cstrong\u003Eirbesartan\u003C/strong\u003E are safe in asthma as they don\u0027t induce cough. Studies have shown no increase in bronchial hyperreactivity with ARBs in hypertensive asthmatics.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECalcium channel blockers like \u003Cstrong\u003Enifedipine\u003C/strong\u003E are excellent choices for hypertension in asthma. They may actually help by opposing smooth muscle contraction in airways, inhibiting mast cell degranulation, and potentially enhancing beta-agonist effects.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis case also highlights the dangers of taking medications prescribed for other people, as they may have serious contraindications or interactions with existing conditions and medications.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Beta-blockers are contraindicated in asthma due to antagonism of beta-agonist bronchodilators.","Taking another person\u0027s prescription medications is dangerous due to potential contraindications and drug interactions.","New onset dyspnoea in a previously well-controlled asthmatic should prompt medication review."],"references":["UpToDate [Internet]. www.uptodate.com. [cited 2022 Nov 18]. Available from: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/treatment-of-hypertension-in-asthma-and-copd?search=hypertension%20in%20asthma\u0026source=search_result\u0026selectedTitle=1~150\u0026usage_type=default\u0026display_rank=1#H5","Practitioners TRAC of general. Management of hypertension in general practice [Internet]. Australian Family Physician. Available from: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2012/may/management-of-hypertension-in-general-practice","\u200cHeart Foundation. Guideline for the diagnosis and management of hypertension in adults [Internet]. 2016. Available from: https://www.heartfoundation.org.au/getmedia/c83511ab-835a-4fcf-96f5-88d770582ddc/PRO-167_Hypertension-guideline-2016_WEB.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"46372"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12264"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"46372","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/46372"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-14T16:00:34+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-14T16:02:49+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4786"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"60927"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"43","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/43"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d